      "preview_head": "list of tips that will help you make the most of your freshman year. 1. Crack your door open You\u2019ll find that some of the best friends you\u2019ll make can be found on your floor or in your building. Make ",
      "preview_tail": " mean you have forgotten about those who love, support your most important relationships by maintaining regular communication and returning visits when possible\u2014it can help keep a sense balance in all",
      "full_text": "list of tips that will help you make the most of your freshman year. 1. Crack your door open You\u2019ll find that some of the best friends you\u2019ll make can be found on your floor or in your building. Make yourself accessible by leaving the door open, especially during common social times like evenings and weekends. 2. Get involved early Clubs are a great way to meet people who share similar interests with yours; they're also excellent opportunities for learning new skills outside of class time that can enrich your college experience in various ways\u2014whether it's improving public speaking, honing leadership abilities or simply having fun while doing something you love. 3. Utilize resources Most colleges and universities offer a plethora of services designed to help students succeed: academic advisories for choosing the right courses; career centers with internship opportunities like Vocatio that Paula interned at over summer break\u2014these are just two examples among many others available on campus or online, so take advantage! 4. Manage your time wisely Balancing schoolwork and social life is a challenge in college but an essential skill to develop early for future success. 5. Embrace change with open arms Your freshman year will be full of 'firsts': the first big test week; dining hall food that's finally starting not just taste like cardboard (at least, most days); your newfound freedom and responsibility... all these experiences are part what makes college unique\u2014and they're worth embracing fully. 6. Stay connected with family While it\u2019ll be tempting to dive headfirst into the independence of campus life after moving out for schooling away from home doesn't mean you have forgotten about those who love, support your most important relationships by maintaining regular communication and returning visits when possible\u2014it can help keep a sense balance in all",
      "avg_prediction": 0.6427,
